  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, it is a felony to launder money in the United States, and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the illegal process of concealing the origins of money obtained through criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or tax evasion, by making it appear as though it came from legitimate sources.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. These laws make it a federal crime to engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activities. Penalties for money laundering can be severe and may include:\n\n- Up to **20 years in federal prison** for each count.\n- **Fines** of up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n- **Asset forfeiture**, where the government can seize property involved in or derived from money laundering.\n\nMoney laundering can also be prosecuted at the state level, where penalties may vary depending on the jurisdiction but are similarly severe.\n\nEngaging in money laundering or related activities, such as structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements, can result in serious legal consequences. Always consult with a legal professional if you have questions about specific situations or laws.",
